Review of dplyr

Functions

It has 7 useful functions:

  • %>%
  • arrange
  • group_by
  • mutate
  • summarise
  • select
  • filter

Some comments

  • A different syntax (less quotations, less dollar signs)
  • Uses dataframes, more than variables
  • Very fast

%>%

This means "then".

  cook it %>%
  eat it

Let's practice

I like animals. Let's get some data about them.

animals <- MASS::Animals

Some questions

  1. Use head to see what our data looks like.

  2. Create a plot with the body variable on the x-axis and the brain variable on the y-axis.

  3. Create a variable called name. This will simply be the row.names(animals).

  4. Create an object called animals. This will be animals (over-write), but use mutate to divide brain by 1,000 in order to convert from grams to kilograms.

Questions (continued)

  1. Create an object called animals. This will be animals (over-write), but use mutate to create an object called brain_to_body which will be brain weight divided by body weight.

  2. Create an object called animals. This will be animals, but use arrange to order by our new variable (brain_to_body).

  3. Which animal has the greatest brain to body ratio? And the least?

Questions (continued)

  1. Use mutate to create a variable in animals which will be called intelligence. If the brain_to_body ratio is greater than 0.15, let's say "smart"; otherwise, let's say "stupid". Hint: use ifelse

  2. Create an object called x. This will be animals, then group_by the intelligence variable, then use summarise to create two new variables: (1) the number of animals, and (2) the average body size of those animals.

More practice

Let's get some data on birth weight.

bw <- MASS::birthwt

Questions on birthweight

  1. Use head to look at our data.

  2. Create a histogram to show the distribution of birthweight.

  3. Create a plot showing the correlation between age (of mother) and the birth weight.

  4. In bw, use mutate to create a new variable called size. If the birth weight is greater than 2500, call it "big"; otherwise, "small".

  5. Create an object called x. This will be bw, then group by our smoke varible AND then use summarise to create a new variable called average_grams which will be the average birth weight.

  6. What is the effect of smoking on birth weight?

More practice

Some questions

  1. Create an object called phone. This will be wb but filtered so as to only include those rows where the indicator_name is "Mobile cellular subscriptions".

  2. Make a plot of the number of of cell phone subscriptions.

  3. Create an object called mulungos. This will be wb but filtered so as to only include those rows where the indicator_name is ""International tourism, number of arrivals" AND the year is greater than 2000.

  4. Make a plot of the number of tourists.

More questions

Let's use our census data again.

  1. Create two new variables using mutate: (1) longitude_round and (2) latitude_round. This should be a rounding to one digit of the coordinates.
census <- 
  census %>%
  mutate(longitude_round = round(longitude, digits = 1),
         latitude_round = round(latitude, digits = 1))
